  . who walked right into my heart! What a dear, kind, honest little man! He staid a good while and we got on beautifully. He regretted much not seeing you—is here about the Committee on his Irish affairsA select committee had been set up in April to inquire into destitution in Donegal; its first meeting was on 13 May. Hill gave evidence that there was no destitution on his estate in Gweedore, Donegal, 23 and 24 June. The last meeting was on 9 July; the final report, 12 July, agreed with Hill.—is to leave London on Saturday. Aubrey de VereAubrey de Vere was an old friend of both Carlyles. found him going—and staid an hour or so, making me lie on the sofa, and talking to me about Death. Then after tea, when I thought it all over, came Mr VaughanHenry Halford Vaughan (1811–85; 
  ODNB
; see 16:303 and 29:41–42

    TC to JWC, 20 July 1843

    , and TC to LA, 4 March 1854


  ), regius prof. of modern history, Oxford, 1848–85; m., 1856, Adeline Maria Jackson (1837–81), da. of Dr. John Jackson (1804–87) and Maria Pattle (1818–92). Julia Margaret Cameron, b. Pattle (1815–79;
  ODNB
) was her aunt.—who looked not sure that I would receive him—and was very embarrassed and comfortless during his short stay.He may have been uncertain of his welcome from JWC as she was a close friend of Ellen Twisleton, and would have known of the growing rift between Vaughan and Edward Twisleton, friends for many years. The rift was partly due to Twisleton’s membership of the Oxford University Commission and his support of its decree that professors should reside in their colleges; Vaughan refused to do this and had resigned from Oxford earlier in 1858 when professorial residence became mandatory. JWC’s friendship with Twisleton’s sister-in-law, Elisabeth Cabot, b. Dwight (1830–91), may have added to his discomfort. Before his marriage Vaughan and Elisabeth had apparently formed a romantic attachment; she had certainly been one of his admirers. By Dec. 1857, shortly after her marriage to James Elliot Cabot (1821–1903), she wrote to her sister that she hoped Vaughan would “succeed in getting himself quite comfortable, at last, he does enough about it for six common men” (MS: Schlesinger Lib. A-99 Cabot Papers, folder 16); in Dec. 1858 she wrote of his marriage: “I always knew Adeline wouldn’t find it what she expected, & am glad Mr Vaughan can have natural feeling for his child, since he can’t for his wife” (Cabot Papers, folder 16). The man is quite spoilt!

There! My Dear! I send you a wonderful communication—a map of your new ‘parish’ and Township in Australia!Carlyle was on the Murray River, about 180 mi. N of Melbourne; Charles Gavan Duffy (1816–1903; 
  ODNB
; see 30:biographical note), member of the legislative assembly of the state of Victoria (est. 1851), who was in charge of the lands department 1858–59, had named it (see Duffy 202). The streets were called Thomas, Jane, Irving, Thackeray, and “Stuart-Mill”; for the plan, see above; for JWC’s drawing of the plan, see JWC to TC, [22 July]. In Oct., “Duffy’s township of Carlyle” was “nearly, if not wholly, under water” after the Murray flooded (Border Post, 8 Oct.). The streets and buildings of the township no longer exist; the nearest town to its position is Rutherglen. I have spent an hour over the packet, before I could understand what it all meant—the letter accompanying the maps was inserted between them so that it was not discovered at first. There are six copies of this map that I send you, and there is a large coloured map on excessively thick paper professing to be

I went in an omnibus to PutneyAbout 3 mi. SE of Chelsea, on the S side of the Thames. yesterday evening and came back outside. It is as pleasant as a Barouche and four the top of an Omnibus but the Conductors dont like the trouble of helping one up— When I came home at six, I found Charlotte wildly excited over Mrs CameronJulia Margaret Cameron.—who had waited for me more than an hour, played on the piano, and written “a long letter on three sheets of paper”— Certainly she had spoiled three sheets, in telling me that she had come to carry me off to Little Holland House,In Kensington; home of Henry Thoby Prinsep (1792–1878; 
  ODNB
), of the British-administered civil service in India, and Sara Monckton Prinsep, b. Pattle (1816–87); m. 1835; she was Julia Margaret Cameron’s sister and a socialite who “would assemble all the available artists of any sort she could find, to swell the cast of her Sunday at-homes, which went on the year round” (R. B. Martin, Tennyson [Oxford, 1980] 407). The Tennysons were among her regular visitors. and that she would send back the Carriage for me at nine—and bring me home at eleven—Charlotte told her I had been very ill and was never out late—but that made no difference—the carriage would be sent—only—if I would not come she (Charlotte) must come over to little Holland House and tell them in time to stop the carriage! “It was a long way to send a carriage for nothing” She did not consider it was a long way for my only servant to be sent for nothing!—While I was hesitating about sending—for of course I never dreamt of 
going—Mr Newberg came to tea—and needing Charlotte at home I found it too absurd that she should have to leave me to get the tea, while she went for Mrs Camerons whim to Holland House!— So I wrote a note and cooly gave it to the Coachman to take back instead of myself— The Tennysons were there and “would be so pleased to see me!” “Alfred was going to Norway and Mrs Tennyson to her Fathers in Lancashire”Tennyson sailed to Norway, 23 July, while Emily went to the house of her father, Henry Sellwood (1782–1867), in Horncastle, Lincolnshire (not “Lancashire,” as JWC wrote). They would not have time to call here— I could not but think the main object in all this was to make me understand there was no outrake for me at Freshwater“Outrake” means “opportunity” here, rather than “expedition.”— I think it would have been common politeness in Mrs Tennyson to have told me herself something of their plans after sending that message by Woolner and having it half acceptedSee TC to JWC, 11 July
.— And Miss Baring! how very absurd of her to ask me at all when she had no real wish about it—

Yesterday morning I had made a confused sleep of it,—sleep divided into 3 (or 2½), and the last an hour too long;—I concluded to execute, that day, a purpose I had been vaguely forming, to go without dinner. Long ride, say to Scotsbrig; tea and caudled egg there, with certain Books from John: that wd be the method. Austin hearing of the thing, and finding the day bad for hay, proposed zealously the gig instead of riding, “Mary to go too,” &c &c: and for
a quiet life, I yielded. The gig did very well,—I got on behind for most part (gig is of dog-cart build), kept the carriage steadier there, and was dispensed with in the way of talk (a very great convenience to me, and unluckily not common in such cases);—tea and egg did very well; everything did well enough; and today I am plus all my lent Books (Tourgff vol II Scènes de la vie russe , vol 2. for one, whh I shall be ready to send you soon); and have brought a “Continental Bradshaw”Railway guide. to boot, if I could look into it without a shudder!— — IsabellaIsabella Carlyle. was in the act of writing to you, she said: no doubt her Note will arrive along with this, tho’ perhaps it will not tell you much. I am glad to hear of Landhall:Lann Hall, Janet Pringle’s home. it wd have been a kind of burble there otherwise. If you could stay in this Country, I find there is no want of possibility: Cressfield House near Ecclefechan, for example, is to be had furnished (and I think even a brougham with it), on extraordinarily equal terms!Cressfield House had belonged to the sisters Mary and Maxwell Little (the Misses Little; see 23:114 TC to JAC, 19 Sept. 1848
). Mary d. in 1857 (see 33:19 TC to JAC, 12 Aug. 1857
); presumably Maxwell had also died. TC’s father, James Carlyle, had built the house in the early 1800s; see Carlyle, Reminiscences 36. In the 1861 census, only a groom and domestic servant are listed as living there. And I had even thots of building (as a permanent Country House for us) some Cottage, on fewed groundThe tenure of land in perpetuity in return for an annual fee. (a la Macdiarmid)John M’Diarmid. among the romantic sea-cliffs of ColvendParish in Kirkcudbrightshire, 18 mi. SSW of Dumfries. or elsewhere:—you have only to get a little stronger, you see! I am very anxious indeed to hear what Bay House does: if you can keep yourself unflurried (but what a task is that, when a day of Larkin sets you all in flame!) I promise myself marked results. So far as locality goes there is no better coast in all the Island.

